'''Felicity Anne Huntingford''' [[FRSE]] (born 17 June 1948)<ref>{{cite news | last = | first = | title = Birthdays | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | location = | pages = 37 | language = | publisher = | date = 17 June 2014 | url = | accessdate = 17 June 2014 }}</ref> is an [[aquatic ecologist]] known for her work in fish behaviour.
== Career == Huntingford's research interests include the aggression in sticklebacks and welfare of farmed fish.
She is the author and editor of several widely cited and reviewed books,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halliday|first=Tim|date=|title=Roots of Aggression|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Qe_hJ8qZb7oC=snippet&q=huntingford|journal=New Scientist|volume=115|issue=1571|pages=57|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Demarest|first=Jack|date=1985|title=Review of: The Study of Animal Behaviour|url=|journal=The Quarterly Review of Biology|volume=60|issue=1|pages=114|doi=10.1086/414275|via=}}</ref> including the textbook ''The Study of Animal Behaviour.''
Huntingford has served as president of the [[Fisheries Society of the British Isles]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fsbi.org.uk/information/history/|title=History of the Society|last=|first=|date=|website=FSBI|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=5 February 2018}}</ref> the [[Association for the Study of Animal Behaviour]], and the [[World Council of Fisheries Societies]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wcfs.fisheries.org/6th-world-fisheries-congress-2012-endinburgh-scotland/|title=6th World Fisheries Congress - 2012 - Edinburgh, Scotland|last=|first=|date=|website=World Council of Fisheries Societies|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=5 February 2018}}</ref> She is Emeritus Professor of Functional Ecology at the [[University of Glasgow]].
==Awards and Honours== Huntingford was elected to the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]] in 1996 in the discipline of organismal and environmental biology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rse.org.uk/fellow/felicity-huntingford/|title=Professor Felicity Ann Huntingford FRSE|website=Royal Society of Edinburgh|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>
Huntingford has presented as an invited lecturer in several named lecture series. Huntingford was awarded the 2001 [[Tinbergen Lecture]] by the [[Association for the Study of Animal Behaviour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asab.org/tinbergen-lecturer/|title=Tinbergen Lecturer|website=ASAB|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> She also delivered the 2012 [[Fisheries Society of the British Isles]] (FSBI) Jack Jones Lecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fsbi.org.uk/conference2012/symposium-theme-2/|title=Symposium Theme: The Physiology of Fish Behaviour|website=FSBI|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>
Huntingford has been honoured with several major academic awards, including the 2006 [[ASAB Medal]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asab.org/asab-medal/|title=The ASAB Medal|website=ASAB|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> and the 2013 FSBI Beverton Medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fsbi.org.uk/information/medals/|title=The medals|website=FSBI|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>
She was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from the Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://internt.slu.se/globalassets/mw/akad-hogtid/utsedda-hedersdoktorer-vid-slu.pdf?si=133F2040973800BF0F82607F1E709150&rid=973130968&sn=sluEPi6-prodSearchIndex|title=Utsedda hedersdoktorer vid SLU (Sveriges lantbruksuniversitet)|website=Swedish University of Agricultural Sciences|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>
