'''Richard E. King''' is Professor of Buddhist and Asian Studies at the [[University of Kent]],<ref name=Kent>{{cite web|title=Professor Richard King|url=http://www.kent.ac.uk/secl/thrs/staff/king.html/|work=Religious Studies|publisher=University of Kent|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> where he specialises in South Asian traditions and [[critical theory]] and [[Religious Studies]].

==Biography==
King obtained his first degree in Philosophy and Theology at [[Hull University]], before completing his PhD in Religious Studies at [[Lancaster University]] in 1993. He was appointed Lecturer in Religious Studies at the [[University of Stirling]] in 1990, where he was subsequently appointed as Reader. In 2000 He moved to [[Derby University]] as Professor and Chair of the Religious Studies department. From 2005 to 2010, he moved to the USA to serve as Professor of Religious Studies at [[Vanderbilt University]]; from there he joined the Department of Theology and Religious Studies at the University of Glasgow in 2010.<ref name=Glasgow>{{cite web|title=Richard King |url=http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/staff/richardking/ |work=Critical Studies Staff |publisher=Wayback Machine |accessdate=7 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711113704/http://www.gla.ac.uk/schools/critical/staff/richardking/ |archivedate=July 11, 2012 }}</ref> In December 2012, he was appointed Professor of Buddhist and Asian Studies in the University of Kent.<ref name=Kent /> He has served as Visiting Professor and guest lecturer at [[Liverpool Hope University|Liverpool Hope]] and [[Cambridge University]].<ref name=Glasgow /> He contributed to the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]]'s exhibition [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041441/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/past/exhibit/2716 "The Third Mind"] as a member of the advisory committee,<ref name=Kent /><ref name=Guggenheim>{{cite web|title=Guggenheim: Books|url=http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/exhibitions/publications/books/items/view/38|work=Books|publisher=Guggenheim Publications|accessdate=7 March 2013}}</ref> and has been invited to offer  public lectures by universities throughout Europe and the USA. He has served as co-chair for the Cultural History for the Study of Religion group for the [[American Academy of Religion]].<ref name=Kent />

